scattered patches, first control initiated in 2008, no follow-up until 2014. Infestation does not seem to be spreading rapidly. Much reduced from 2008.
Just starting to bud. Doesn't seem like that many less than last year, though there are some dead areas that were probably from spray last year where there was none.

Only found 2 plants. (Leah pulled one because she didn't know not to.) Hopefully we can find the one plant again when we come back to spray. It is right near two wooden posts and path through coyote brush.
Bounded on north by rocky point, on south by bullrushes.
with fennel, gumplant, salsola soda, and pickleweed

Only saw a couple little sprouts coming out of sand box.
Plants above ground look dead, but most green at base. Most roots still alive, especially when connected to another plant. Some roots dead a few inches out when not between two plants.

Notes: Many shoots coming up with inflorescence. Seems comprable to last year.
A few scattered seedlings. Area is mostly dead, surrounded by Picris, Conium and Rumex - all coming into treated area.

flowering plants in lower area were 99% brown, but above road still 50% green. The area above road was mowed right before spray (Rangers thought it needed it since that's what we did last year). This might have made herbicide ineffective, or caused appli
about 50% dead. Some leaves dead but stems alive. Others appear to have been missed completely. They also appeared to spray some Atriplex.
a few are flowering, while the rest are showing some signs of die back, but still mostly green.

Source: Dan Gluesenkamp: Bay Area Early Detection Network

Notes: About 1/4 of what was there last year. Just starting to bud. Plants are still small. In lower area not much vegetation coming up. Upland, is all poison hemlock now.
most have died back no. Just scattered green ones. But lots of poison hemlock and thistle coming in. Need to get soemthing else in there.
80% yellowed, rest green, some flowering (must have been missed by herbicide)

from Marjorie Siegel: I have been pulling the pepperweed that already spread outside of the pond area and was planning to pull the rest as I have time. the manager for the Strawberry Recreation District is Leanne Kreuzer at 383 6494
Flowering and/or fruiting plants were removed today. Many rosettes remain.
Shrunk polygon quite a bit, but still a lot, very dense. Ends are dense Poison Hemlock. Still need to get accurate GPS map.

Source: Dan Gluesenkamp: Audubon Canyon Ranch; Bay Area Early Detection Network, BAEDN
Notes: Probably MCOSD land. Mischon Martin asked MCOSD staff to remove the plants in summer 2008.

Notes: broken line 4-5 m along beach at base of rip-rap
First observation on lower Codornices Creek? What is source? This area is not tidal. Serious threat to restoration. Need to check downstream.
Small patch moving from rocks inland toward water in summer 2015, with inland somewhat crippled, apparently by drought.
Only known patch on east shore of main lagoon. Controlled many years by F5C. Like others, strongly thinned, apparently by drought, summer 2015

Pepperweed here all the way to Bay Trail. Pepperweed has been along shoreline many years, with control efforts since 1999. This area is now part of Eastshore State Park, but managed by City of Berkeley (with Friends of Five Creeks controlling pepperweed)

one year ago, this plant was not observed in this area; this year, it has become a dominant plant in the selected area. Previously, this area was dominated by Wild oat (Avena fatua) and various Brome spp, as well as various thistles in lesser numbers. The area south and east of this area still are dominated by these plants, but I suspect that the pepperweed will continue its rapid spread through the area.
There's only 5 plants now. This will get into alameda creek, and infest the whole downstream section of alameda creek. Extirpate it now!!!
